  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "There's a misunderstanding in your premise. Black holes pull in light and matter due to their extreme gravitational field, not because of mass alone. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. Black holes have immense gravitational pull due to their extremely dense concentration of mass in a small space.\n\n2. According to Einstein's theory of general relativity, gravity is actually the curvature of spacetime. Massive objects like black holes create such a deep \"well\" in spacetime that even massless things like light cannot escape once they cross the event horizon.\n\n3. Light is affected by gravity, even though it has no rest mass. Light follows the curvature of spacetime created by massive objects.\n\n4. The gravitational pull of a black hole is so strong that its escape velocity exceeds the speed of light. Since nothing can travel faster than light, nothing can escape once it passes the event horizon.\n\n5. This means black holes pull in both matter and light, not just matter.\n\nThe key point is that gravity affects all forms of energy and matter, not just objects with traditional mass. The extreme density and spacetime curvature of black holes create their powerful gravitational effects.\n\nSo black holes can and do exist, pulling in everything that comes too close, including light.",
